00:26:06,838 --> 00:26:08,660
Look at this.

475
00:26:11,190 --> 00:26:15,412
Aww. Oh, no.

476
00:26:15,478 --> 00:26:18,860
You could have given us
one more winter.

477
00:26:22,198 --> 00:26:24,915
- Is it open?
- Yes, Jeremiah. I left it open.

478
00:26:24,982 --> 00:26:27,403
- Okay? All right. Sleep well.
- Okay.

479
00:26:27,478 --> 00:26:29,333
Good night, Mommy.

480
00:26:29,398 --> 00:26:31,220
What a night.

481
00:26:31,318 --> 00:26:33,806
I don't even want
to think about tomorrow...

482
00:26:33,878 --> 00:26:37,490
between the boiler and Hakim leaving.

483
00:26:37,558 --> 00:26:40,689
Now, why... why are they
gonna send that boy...

484
00:26:40,758 --> 00:26:42,929
to a foster home so far away?

485
00:26:42,998 --> 00:26:44,853
I knew I should have called...

486
00:26:44,918 --> 00:26:47,220
Honey, you called half
the agencies in the state.

487
00:26:47,318 --> 00:26:50,133
I know, I know.

488
00:26:50,198 --> 00:26:52,816
But maybe the answer
was in the other half.

489
00:26:56,982 --> 00:26:59,087
I'm losing them, Julia.

490
00:26:59,158 --> 00:27:03,697
One by one.
Hakim, Saul, Billy...

491
00:27:03,766 --> 00:27:06,287
the youth center.

492
00:27:06,358 --> 00:27:10,035
I know it's my fault,
but I just can't seem...

493
00:27:10,102 --> 00:27:13,876
- You know, honey,
I had some thoughts on...
- Can we do this in the morning?

494
00:27:13,942 --> 00:27:16,113
'Cause I'm beat.

495
00:27:19,638 --> 00:27:21,940
Yeah, the morning's fine.

496
00:27:23,638 --> 00:27:26,485
Good night, Julia.

497
00:27:36,022 --> 00:27:38,989
Yoo-hoo! Mornin'!

498
00:27:39,062 --> 00:27:41,266
Whoo!
I brought the mail in.

499
00:27:43,798 --> 00:27:45,652
Anybody wanna open it?

500
00:27:45,718 --> 00:27:49,296
Oh. Well, I'll just
take my coat off...

501
00:27:49,366 --> 00:27:51,602
and bring it on
into the office, then.

502
00:27:51,670 --> 00:27:55,729
Look, I know things have been tough
around here lately, and that's my fault.

503
00:27:55,798 --> 00:27:57,969
But everything is gonna be all right.

504
00:27:58,038 --> 00:28:02,032
- [Phone Ringing]
- I'm comin'! Ooh! I got it!

505
00:28:02,102 --> 00:28:04,174
Hello? Who?

506
00:28:04,278 --> 00:28:06,612
- Mm-hmm.
- If only saying it made it all right.

507
00:28:06,678 --> 00:28:09,231
- Yeah.
- You see? If you'd listened,
you'd have heard an apology.

508
00:28:09,302 --> 00:28:11,058
Not a big one, but a start.

509
00:28:11,125 --> 00:28:13,133
- Uh-huh.
- No, what I heard is a man saying...

510
00:28:13,206 --> 00:28:16,369
"How can I deal with this fast enough,
then get on with the rest of my day?"

511
00:28:16,438 --> 00:28:19,536
- You see, that's not fair.
- Oh, it's not fair?

512
00:28:19,606 --> 00:28:21,995
Girl, I'm trying to listen!

513
00:28:22,070 --> 00:28:25,518
[Laughs] Yeah, I'll give him
the message. Uh-huh.

514
00:28:25,590 --> 00:28:27,891
We've got to stop talking around Mama.
She knows too much of our business.

515
00:28:27,957 --> 00:28:31,754
That was Anna Eldridge. Billy's
bail hearing's been scheduled for 9:30.

516
00:28:31,830 --> 00:28:35,310
9:30! We'll finish this later, honey.
I promise.

517
00:28:35,381 --> 00:28:37,520
- Are you coming home after?
- Not right after.

518
00:28:37,590 --> 00:28:40,045
- I have to be somewhere at 11:00.
- Joe Hamilton.

519
00:28:40,118 --> 00:28:43,315
- Do you mind?
- Oh, Henry.

520
00:28:43,382 --> 00:28:46,643
Do I look like I mind?

521
00:28:52,886 --> 00:28:55,220
You ready to talk about this,
little girl?

522
00:28:55,318 --> 00:28:58,798
I don't know what you mean, Mama.
I think things are looking up for us.

523
00:28:58,870 --> 00:29:02,612
Mmm-hmm.
There goes that behind again.

524
00:29:02,678 --> 00:29:06,289
% I know He's keeping me alive%

525
00:29:06,357 --> 00:29:08,048
% Keeping me alive%

526
00:29:08,118 --> 00:29:09,973
% Dum, dum, dum, dum, dum%

527
00:29:10,038 --> 00:29:12,886
% He's all over me%

528
00:29:12,950 --> 00:29:14,128
% And He's keepin' me alive%

529
00:29:14,198 --> 00:29:17,165
% Oooh, yeah
He's all over me%

530
00:29:17,238 --> 00:29:19,889
% Ooh-ooh, keepin' me alive%

531
00:29:19,958 --> 00:29:22,925
% And He's all over me%

532
00:29:22,998 --> 00:29:25,365
% Ooh-ooh, keepin'... % %
[Screams, Gasps]

533
00:29:25,430 --> 00:29:28,015
I'm sorry.
I didn't mean to frighten you.

534
00:29:28,085 --> 00:29:30,289
I didn't hear you come in!
You waitin' for the pastor?

535
00:29:30,357 --> 00:29:32,529
Yes, yes.
My name's Dudley.

536
00:29:32,598 --> 00:29:34,965
- Beverly.
- How are you?

537
00:29:35,030 --> 00:29:37,615
- I'm the pastor's secretary.
- Pleasure to meet you.

538
00:29:37,685 --> 00:29:40,555
You just missed him.
He went to court.

539
00:29:40,630 --> 00:29:43,761
- These your children?
- Yeah, that's them.

540
00:29:43,830 --> 00:29:45,685
Oh, they're beautiful.

541
00:29:45,750 --> 00:29:48,368
Where was your husband?
Taking the picture?

542
00:29:48,438 --> 00:29:52,879
Mm-hmm.
Then he took the car and the waitress
at the diner and moved to Cleveland.

543
00:29:52,950 --> 00:29:56,179
- Sorry to hear that.
- You have any children?

544
00:29:56,246 --> 00:30:01,483
No, no. Never had a chance
to settle down. I wanted to.

545
00:30:01,558 --> 00:30:05,813
- [Gasps]
- You smell wonderful.
What do you call that?

546
00:30:05,877 --> 00:30:07,306
Soap.

547
00:30:07,382 --> 00:30:09,968
I haven't smelled a woman
in such a long time.

548
00:30:10,038 --> 00:30:13,485
I'll get you a bar for Christmas.
Do you have an appointment?

549
00:30:13,557 --> 00:30:17,169
Uh, no, not exactly.
I was...

550
00:30:17,238 --> 00:30:20,533
sent to help the reverend,
like an assistant.

551
00:30:20,598 --> 00:30:24,045
Assistant? I haven't
heard anything about no...

552
00:30:24,117 --> 00:30:26,092
Oh, my Lord!
Am I gettin' fired?

553
00:30:26,166 --> 00:30:28,173
No, no, no.
It's just temporary.

554
00:30:28,278 --> 00:30:30,612
Temporary! I ain't heard
nothing about no temporary!

555
00:30:30,678 --> 00:30:32,685
- Well, there's nothing... Uh, look.
- Oh, God.

556
00:30:32,757 --> 00:30:35,954
- Let me get you some coffee.
- Coffee!
You made coffee on that machine?

557
00:30:36,022 --> 00:30:39,404
I've been trying for six weeks
to figure out that machine!

558
00:30:39,477 --> 00:30:41,812
My babies need new glasses,
and I'm out of a job!

559
00:30:41,878 --> 00:30:44,082
Look, mister, I have kids.
They're growin' like weeds.

560
00:30:44,150 --> 00:30:47,084
And if you think I get a penny from that
man, you got another thought comin'!

561
00:30:47,157 --> 00:30:49,197
I can't take this!
Bein' fired!

562
00:30:49,270 --> 00:30:51,180
Take it easy.
There's nothing to worry about. Here.

563
00:30:51,286 --> 00:30:53,620
[Sobbing]
Oooh! Oooh!

564
00:30:53,686 --> 00:30:55,889
Look at you.
You're crying.

565
00:30:55,958 --> 00:30:58,129
Here, blow, blow.

566
00:30:58,198 --> 00:31:00,849
Oh. I knew that.
[Blowing Nose]

567
00:31:00,918 --> 00:31:04,529
Your Honor, my client,
Billy Eldridge...

568
00:31:04,597 --> 00:31:06,572
was sent by his mother
to return a video rental...

569
00:31:06,646 --> 00:31:09,166
[Judge]
It's all here, Miss Chattan.

570
00:31:09,237 --> 00:31:11,758
Well, the Reverend Biggs
is present in the courtroom...

571
00:31:11,830 --> 00:31:14,197
and he is willing to post bail.

572
00:31:14,262 --> 00:31:17,164
This is a serious felony.
Bail is set at $ 25,000.

573
00:31:17,238 --> 00:31:20,685
- Your Honor, I have evidence...
- May I address the court?

574
00:31:20,757 --> 00:31:23,375
I'm turning it over
for grand jury action. Next case.

575
00:31:23,446 --> 00:31:25,333
We love you, Billy.
He didn't do it.

576
00:31:25,398 --> 00:31:26,991
[Judge]
Clear the court.

577
00:31:27,062 --> 00:31:29,615
$25,000!
What am I gonna do?

578
00:31:29,686 --> 00:31:32,337
- Would you clear the court?
- I'll take care of it.

579
00:31:32,406 --> 00:31:35,308
Next case.
I said, next case!

580
00:31:35,382 --> 00:31:38,229
[Bailiff]
Pending 802, Harley Williamson.

581
00:31:44,630 --> 00:31:46,485
[Doorbell Ringing]

582
00:31:51,766 --> 00:31:54,352
[Distant Knocking]

583
00:31:59,446 --> 00:32:01,137
- You could hide.
- Mm-mm.

584
00:32:01,206 --> 00:32:04,108
- Take this. I'll bring him right out.
- Sure. No problem.

585
00:32:10,742 --> 00:32:12,945
Here.
They might starve you.

586
00:32:14,677 --> 00:32:17,394
Thanks.

587
00:32:22,742 --> 00:32:25,393
Okay, they've got everything.
All ready to go.

588
00:32:25,462 --> 00:32:27,534
Hey, guys!

589
00:32:27,605 --> 00:32:30,191
Hakim, you remember
Robbie, don't you?

590
00:32:30,262 --> 00:32:32,117
Hakim gets to ride
in the train today.

591
00:32:32,182 --> 00:32:36,011
Wow. A train ride.

592
00:32:36,085 --> 00:32:37,995
We're running a little late.

593
00:32:38,069 --> 00:32:40,241
Okay.

594
00:32:40,310 --> 00:32:44,271
Take care of yourself, okay?
See you soon. Say good-bye, Jer.

595
00:32:44,341 --> 00:32:46,927
Bye.

596
00:32:46,998 --> 00:32:49,235
Take care.

597
00:32:49,302 --> 00:32:51,276
Bye, Hakim.
We'll miss you.

598
00:32:53,365 --> 00:32:55,951
Hold on, baby.
It's cold out here.

599
00:33:03,766 --> 00:33:06,319
Who will I tell my secrets to?

600
00:33:06,390 --> 00:33:08,975
Well, you can phone Hakim
sometimes, okay?

601
00:33:09,045 --> 00:33:12,144
And Mommy'll teach you how to write,
so you can send him letters.

602
00:33:23,670 --> 00:33:25,557
Bye.

603
00:33:45,238 --> 00:33:48,402
I know You have
a master plan, but...

604
00:33:48,470 --> 00:33:51,153
sometimes You're just
a little tough to figure.

605
00:33:52,726 --> 00:33:55,093
Jeremiah.

606
00:33:55,158 --> 00:33:58,573
- Jeremiah.
- It's not fair!

607
00:33:58,645 --> 00:34:00,979
Hakim left.

608
00:34:03,765 --> 00:34:07,180
[Crying]

609
00:34:07,285 --> 00:34:09,903
[Beverly]
Julia.

610
00:34:12,949 --> 00:34:15,316
This is Dudley,
the reverend's new assistant.

611
00:34:15,381 --> 00:34:19,156
Assistant? He wrote to the church
council months ago for extra help.

612
00:34:19,221 --> 00:34:21,774
Well, the extra help is here.

613
00:34:21,845 --> 00:34:24,812
Oooooh.

614
00:34:24,885 --> 00:34:28,333
But he didn't say anything about getting
a response. Who sent you, exactly?

615
00:34:28,405 --> 00:34:30,739
Uh, the, uh...
[Clears Throat]

616
00:34:30,805 --> 00:34:33,009
The Top Man himself,
Mrs. Biggs.

617
00:34:33,077 --> 00:34:34,932
- Julia.
- Julia.

618
00:34:34,997 --> 00:34:37,005
[Clears Throat]

619
00:34:37,078 --> 00:34:40,176
And this is Julia's mother,
Mrs. Coleman.

620
00:34:40,245 --> 00:34:42,133
[Dudley]
Of course it is.

621
00:34:42,198 --> 00:34:46,606
Well, it's obvious where
Julia's beauty comes from.

622
00:34:46,678 --> 00:34:50,606
Oh. And me with my hair
lookin' like this.

623
00:34:50,678 --> 00:34:53,296
- Oh, no. It looks magnificent.
- Why, thank you.

624
00:34:53,365 --> 00:34:56,529
- Well, Mr., um...
- You can call me Dudley.

625
00:34:56,598 --> 00:34:58,769
- Dudley. You're very welcome here.
- Thank you.

626
00:34:58,837 --> 00:35:01,139
Excuse us.

627
00:35:03,510 --> 00:35:05,364
What are you doing?

628
00:35:05,430 --> 00:35:07,699
Now, that's what I call good-lookin'!
[Laughing]

629
00:35:07,765 --> 00:35:09,969
Your daddy used to look
like that back in 19...

630
00:35:10,038 --> 00:35:13,300
Ma, ma, ma.
I've heard it 100 times.

631
00:35:13,366 --> 00:35:17,872
Yeah, well, maybe now,
with him around, you'll have time to
deal with some of your own problems.

632
00:35:17,941 --> 00:35:19,796
[Julia] The Good Lord's
the only one who can do that.

633
00:35:19,861 --> 00:35:22,098
- Honey, you don't mean that.
- Yeah, I do.

634
00:35:22,165 --> 00:35:24,020
Ma!

635
00:35:24,085 --> 00:35:27,380
I was gonna go over
by the window, Julia.

636
00:35:27,445 --> 00:35:28,787
There's too many rules
in this house.

637
00:35:40,405 --> 00:35:42,576
[Gasping]
You're the man in the street...

638
00:35:42,645 --> 00:35:45,493
and in the snow and...

639
00:35:45,558 --> 00:35:47,697
My name's Dudley.

640
00:35:47,766 --> 00:35:49,969
I'm here to help your father.

641
00:35:50,038 --> 00:35:53,714
- I'm Jeremiah.
- It's nice to meet you, Jeremiah.

642
00:35:53,782 --> 00:35:55,920
You've got a real nice room here.

643
00:35:55,989 --> 00:35:57,484
Thank you.

644
00:35:57,557 --> 00:36:00,819
Wow, you've got a lot
of neat stuff in here.

645
00:36:00,885 --> 00:36:02,893
And what is this?

646
00:36:02,965 --> 00:36:05,999
My toy ambulance is broken.

647
00:36:06,070 --> 00:36:09,331
The battery got stole,
and the lights don't work anymore.

648
00:36:09,398 --> 00:36:13,708
Is that right?
I'll see what I can do here.

649
00:36:13,781 --> 00:36:16,815
[Siren Wailing]

650
00:36:16,885 --> 00:36:18,990
It never had a siren!

651
00:36:21,526 --> 00:36:23,380
Never had a siren?

652
00:36:23,446 --> 00:36:25,268
No.

653
00:36:30,805 --> 00:36:36,043
You look sad there, Jeremiah.
Have you been crying?

654
00:36:36,117 --> 00:36:38,605
Yes.

655
00:36:38,677 --> 00:36:41,579
I'm sorry
about your friend, Hakim.

656
00:36:43,285 --> 00:36:46,417
What if I told you...

657
00:36:46,486 --> 00:36:48,657
that he's not really gone?

658
00:36:48,725 --> 00:36:52,500
Hakim?
Did he run away and come back?

659
00:36:52,565 --> 00:36:56,788
- No, he never left.
- Yes, he did. I saw him go.

660
00:36:59,670 --> 00:37:03,761
Well, you know, my mother...

661
00:37:03,829 --> 00:37:06,218
once lost someone
who was very dear to her.

662
00:37:06,325 --> 00:37:08,594
He wasn't as young as Hakim,
but he was...

663
00:37:08,662 --> 00:37:10,996
too young, just the same.

664
00:37:11,061 --> 00:37:14,989
And she would always do something
that seemed to make her feel better.

665
00:37:15,061 --> 00:37:17,396
- You want to try it?
- Yeah.

666
00:37:17,462 --> 00:37:19,698
All right, close your eyes.

667
00:37:19,765 --> 00:37:24,272
Do you remember
playing in the snow with Hakim?

668
00:37:26,261 --> 00:37:29,556
Do you remember
what his laugh sounded like?

669
00:37:29,621 --> 00:37:31,858
Yes.

670
00:37:31,925 --> 00:37:35,700
Do you remember
what he looked like catching a ball?

671
00:37:35,765 --> 00:37:41,232
He never caught the ball in his life.
But I remember.

672
00:37:41,302 --> 00:37:45,044
That's because when God
takes someone away from us...

673
00:37:45,109 --> 00:37:49,451
He leaves what's most important
about that person with us.

674
00:37:49,525 --> 00:37:51,533
Right here in our hearts.

675
00:37:51,605 --> 00:37:55,534
Yeah, but I still miss him.

676
00:37:55,606 --> 00:37:58,355
Well, she still misses him too.

677
00:37:58,421 --> 00:38:01,072
Are you all right?

678
00:38:01,141 --> 00:38:04,786
Maybe you should close your eyes.

679
00:38:09,750 --> 00:38:12,652
Mommy says I can write to him.

680
00:38:12,725 --> 00:38:15,092
- Do you know how to spell his name?
- No.

681
00:38:15,158 --> 00:38:17,711
- You want to learn? All right.
- Yeah!

682
00:38:17,781 --> 00:38:20,913
- Hakim starts with an "H."
- And ends with "akim."

683
00:38:20,981 --> 00:38:23,981
- There you go. Perfect.
- [Laughing]

684
00:38:26,005 --> 00:38:27,827
Wow!

685
00:38:30,037 --> 00:38:33,070
Fishies in a TV.

686
00:38:36,886 --> 00:38:39,668
[Computerized Fanfare]

687
00:38:50,230 --> 00:38:52,564
Windows.

688
00:39:09,365 --> 00:39:11,787
Henry?

689
00:39:11,861 --> 00:39:15,057
I know I said
make an appointment...

690
00:39:15,125 --> 00:39:18,354
but I didn't say anything
about filling out any form.

691
00:39:18,422 --> 00:39:20,178
[Sighing]

692
00:39:20,277 --> 00:39:24,172
Beverly!
Beverly, I need you.

693
00:39:24,245 --> 00:39:28,620
I gave her the day off to do
some Christmas shopping, Henry.

694
00:39:30,485 --> 00:39:32,657
You gave my secretary the day...

695
00:39:32,725 --> 00:39:35,180
Yes, she needed some time off
to be with her children...

696
00:39:35,285 --> 00:39:38,100
and I needed time to do my job with you.

697
00:39:38,165 --> 00:39:41,067
- What job? What are you doing here?
- Henry, Henry, Henry!

698
00:39:41,141 --> 00:39:43,181
How many times I got to tell you?

699
00:39:43,285 --> 00:39:46,187
I'm here in answer to your request
for help. And Julia's.

700
00:39:46,262 --> 00:39:50,222
You can forget about the boiler.
You got more important problem...

701
00:39:50,325 --> 00:39:52,180
Ah, here she is now.

702
00:39:52,245 --> 00:39:54,416
- [Julia] Henry?
- Wha...

703
00:39:54,485 --> 00:39:56,907
[Marguerite]
Whoo! Lord have mercy!

704
00:39:56,981 --> 00:40:01,716
Honey, remind me the next time I pay
a visit, I wanna get paid! Okay?

705
00:40:01,781 --> 00:40:04,017
- [Laughing]
- Hi, Dudley.

706
00:40:04,085 --> 00:40:08,395
- Julia.
- Dudley. D-U-D-L-E-Y.

707
00:40:08,469 --> 00:40:10,891
- Perfect.
- [Julia] Very good.

708
00:40:10,965 --> 00:40:14,413
- Poi-fect. Poi-fect.
- What happened with Billy Eldridge?

709
00:40:14,485 --> 00:40:17,169
Uh, uh, the judge
set the bail at $25,000.

710
00:40:17,238 --> 00:40:20,085
- Henry, that child's still in jail?
- Julia, I did what I could!

711
00:40:20,149 --> 00:40:22,964
[Clearing Throat]

712
00:40:23,029 --> 00:40:25,396
Come on, sweetie.
We have a nativity play to rehearse.

713
00:40:25,461 --> 00:40:27,469
You can't rehearse.
It's freezing in there.

714
00:40:27,542 --> 00:40:30,029
Henry, I'll be chasing 15 kids all day.
I don't think I'll get cold.

715
00:40:30,101 --> 00:40:32,654
And after we're through, you're
taking your son shopping, remember?

716
00:40:32,725 --> 00:40:34,099
- Henry.
- Huh?

717
00:40:34,165 --> 00:40:36,685
Your wife's talking to you.

718
00:40:36,757 --> 00:40:40,913
Oh, yes, uh, uh...
Hanley's, 1:00. 1:00?

719
00:40:40,981 --> 00:40:42,956
Spell Hakim for me, baby.

720
00:40:43,029 --> 00:40:47,568
M-l-K-A-H.
Dudley's teaching me to spell backwards.

721
00:40:47,637 --> 00:40:51,052
[Julia] Maybe he can teach Daddy
how to be on time.

722
00:40:51,125 --> 00:40:55,860
These are perfect. Beverly never
typed a perfect letter in her life.

723
00:40:55,925 --> 00:40:58,413
Yes, I did those myself,
once I figured out that fish typewriter.

724
00:40:58,485 --> 00:41:00,340
Let's get this straight, Dud.

725
00:41:00,405 --> 00:41:03,569
I do not appreciate some stranger
coming into my office...

726
00:41:03,637 --> 00:41:06,932
Angels are hardly strangers, Henry.
And don't call me "Dud."

727
00:41:06,997 --> 00:41:09,550
[Marguerite]
Julia, hold on! Wait for me!

728
00:41:09,621 --> 00:41:13,550
Excuse me, Mother, not now. I'm having
a little meeting. You understand.

729
00:41:13,621 --> 00:41:15,410
- Bye, Marguerite!
- Bye, Dudley!

730
00:41:15,477 --> 00:41:17,387
- [Julia] Mama, come on!
- Start that rehearsal!

731
00:41:17,461 --> 00:41:21,455
You are not going around telling
my family this ridiculous story...

732
00:41:21,525 --> 00:41:24,372
No, of course not.
They think the church council sent me.

733
00:41:24,438 --> 00:41:26,325
The church council!

734
00:41:26,389 --> 00:41:29,935
Why don't we continue this on our way
to the meeting with Joe Hamilton?

735
00:41:30,005 --> 00:41:32,176
[Gasps]
The meeting.

736
00:41:32,245 --> 00:41:34,733
- [Dudley] So, which floor is he on?
- [Henry] I'm not telling.

737
00:41:34,805 --> 00:41:36,692
- Henry, what's the floor?
- Go away.

738
00:41:36,757 --> 00:41:40,652
- You asked for help.
- Not from you. I don't need you
in here, out there or anywhere.

739
00:41:42,197 --> 00:41:45,972
You didn't have to let the doors close
on me downstairs, Henry. That was cold.

740
00:41:46,037 --> 00:41:48,044
Well, I figured
you'd just fly up.

741
00:41:48,117 --> 00:41:51,729
You know, if you're really
a you-know-what, where are your wings?

742
00:41:51,797 --> 00:41:53,804
You're caught up in stereotypes, Henry.
That's your problem.

743
00:41:53,877 --> 00:41:55,852
Hello, Reverend.

744
00:41:55,925 --> 00:41:58,892
That's a beautiful dress you have on.
Just magnificent.

745
00:41:58,965 --> 00:42:00,820
Why, thank you.

746
00:42:00,885 --> 00:42:03,568
- You're very welcome.
- [Laughing]

747
00:42:03,637 --> 00:42:05,972
Is Mr. Hamilton inside?

748
00:42:06,037 --> 00:42:09,779
Oh, he's taping another TV commercial,
but you can wait in his office.

749
00:42:09,845 --> 00:42:12,179
- Thank you.
- You're very welcome.

750
00:42:12,245 --> 00:42:14,765
[Phone Ringing]

751
00:42:14,837 --> 00:42:17,520
Hamilton Realty.
Hi, Amy.

752
00:42:17,589 --> 00:42:21,201
You know that old dress
from Mom's closet? It's back in style.

753
00:42:22,485 --> 00:42:24,493
"That's a lovely dress!"

754
00:42:24,565 --> 00:42:27,183
It was a lovely dress. I mean,
you gotta admit, it was a lovely dress.

755
00:42:27,285 --> 00:42:29,457
What kind of angel talks like that?

756
00:42:29,525 --> 00:42:31,859
The kind of angel
that has good taste.

757
00:42:31,925 --> 00:42:33,932
Well, you're still
not going in here.

758
00:42:34,005 --> 00:42:36,656
Henry, I'm like this with the creator
of the entire universe.

759
00:42:36,725 --> 00:42:40,238
- Now, you don't think a little door's
gonna stop me, do you?
- Yes.

760
00:42:40,309 --> 00:42:43,059
How? How?

761
00:42:43,125 --> 00:42:45,263
Rule Number Two.

762
00:42:48,085 --> 00:42:52,395
All right, fine, Henry. Can't make you
do anything you don't wanna do.

763
00:42:52,469 --> 00:42:55,186
That's right! That's right!
I always liked that rule!

764
00:42:56,725 --> 00:42:59,594
Did you like that smile?
I tilted my head to the side.

765
00:42:59,669 --> 00:43:01,557
I loved it.

766
00:43:01,621 --> 00:43:03,857
- Henry Biggs.
- Joe Hamilton.

767
00:43:03,924 --> 00:43:05,932
- How are you doing? Julia's good?
- She's very good.

768
00:43:06,005 --> 00:43:08,012
- [Clears Throat]
- Uh, Henry, this is Debbie Page.

769
00:43:08,085 --> 00:43:10,506
- Hi.
- She's the station manager over at WRKO.

770
00:43:10,581 --> 00:43:12,818
They're televising your Christmas sermon
this year.

771
00:43:12,885 --> 00:43:15,568
We need to get your text
for the TelePrompTer, Reverend.

772
00:43:15,637 --> 00:43:18,899
- I'm working on it.
- Later, Debbie. Come on.
Let's see the guys.

773
00:43:18,965 --> 00:43:20,820
- Wait 'til you see where
you're gonna move to, Henry.
- What?

774
00:43:20,885 --> 00:43:23,787
A planned community.
Your son could ride his bike to school.

775
00:43:23,861 --> 00:43:28,116
[Men Chattering]

776
00:43:28,181 --> 00:43:30,035
- Mary?
- Henry!

777
00:43:30,101 --> 00:43:32,522
Osbert?
What are you doing here?

778
00:43:32,597 --> 00:43:36,175
Well, I, we, um... We came to check out,
the same as you, Henry!

779
00:43:36,245 --> 00:43:38,187
Saul.

780
00:43:38,261 --> 00:43:41,610
Uh, listen to the man, Henry.
We think it makes sense.

781
00:43:41,685 --> 00:43:43,540
Well, of course
it makes sense.

782
00:43:43,605 --> 00:43:45,677
That's what it's gonna look like
when it's finished.

783
00:43:45,749 --> 00:43:48,083
- What do you think, Henry?
- Isn't that nice?

784
00:43:48,149 --> 00:43:50,799
It's a new city landmark.
It's a whole new neighborhood.

785
00:43:50,869 --> 00:43:53,007
A different clientele, so to speak.

786
00:43:53,077 --> 00:43:55,052
I'm hoping, with everyone here,
we can once and for all...

787
00:43:55,125 --> 00:43:58,223
persuade you to move
into the new world, Henry.

788
00:43:58,325 --> 00:44:01,195
Well, all we need is
a boiler that works...

789
00:44:01,269 --> 00:44:03,855
and we'll be fine
in the world that we're in.

790
00:44:03,925 --> 00:44:05,780
[Laughter]

791
00:44:05,845 --> 00:44:10,187
New boiler. Henry, look at this.
Day care facilities.

792
00:44:10,261 --> 00:44:12,269
[Mary]
We need that.

793
00:44:12,340 --> 00:44:14,413
[Osbert]
We could sure use that.

794
00:44:14,485 --> 00:44:16,176
Senior citizens' club.

795
00:44:16,245 --> 00:44:18,317
- That's much better than ours.
- Mm-hmm.

796
00:44:18,389 --> 00:44:21,007
- What I'm offering you here, Henry...
- Well, it is.

797
00:44:21,077 --> 00:44:24,492
TV cameras and lighting
built right in.

798
00:44:24,564 --> 00:44:27,434
- [Saul] Look at that!
- It's a pulpit to preach to the world!

799
00:44:27,509 --> 00:44:29,331
[Mary]
It's beautiful!

800
00:44:29,397 --> 00:44:31,950
All you have to say is,
"I'll do it."

801
00:44:35,605 --> 00:44:37,939
[Whispering]
Say yeah. Say yeah.

802
00:44:38,004 --> 00:44:41,387
All right.

803
00:44:41,461 --> 00:44:44,559
Look, say yes,
and I'll throw in that new boiler.

804
00:44:44,628 --> 00:44:47,378
I'll stop St. Matt's
from freezing over Christmas...

805
00:44:47,445 --> 00:44:50,293
if that's the price
I have to pay to get you.

806
00:44:50,357 --> 00:44:54,896
And if I accept,
what price am I paying?

807
00:44:54,965 --> 00:44:58,893
Henry, what you see there is
the answer to all your problems.

808
00:44:58,965 --> 00:45:00,820
[Osbert] Amen.

809
00:45:00,885 --> 00:45:02,860
Isn't it?

810
00:45:03,061 --> 00:45:06,771
- % % [Children Singing]
- I need my Magi. The Magi's entrance.

811
00:45:06,837 --> 00:45:10,099
- What does the sheep say in this play?
- Baaaa!

812
00:45:10,165 --> 00:45:12,020
Ah. Mmm.

813
00:45:12,085 --> 00:45:14,223
Does everybody know their parts?
You know your parts?

814
00:45:14,325 --> 00:45:18,187
- What's my part?
- What's your part? You're a camel.

815
00:45:18,261 --> 00:45:20,116
- I need my shepherds.
- I'm a shepherd.

816
00:45:20,181 --> 00:45:22,832
- Come here. You two, over here.
- I'm the angel.

817
00:45:22,901 --> 00:45:25,934
- In there. Come on.
- [Children Chattering]

818
00:45:26,004 --> 00:45:29,004
[Julia] Kick it, Mrs. Havergal.
Let's do this.

819
00:45:29,077 --> 00:45:31,761
Jeremiah, get in your place, please.

820
00:45:34,389 --> 00:45:37,967
% Mommies and Daddies%

821
00:45:38,036 --> 00:45:41,866
% Always believe%

822
00:45:41,941 --> 00:45:46,992
% That their little angels%

823
00:45:47,061 --> 00:45:50,890
- % Are special indeed%
- Smile, Michael.

824
00:45:50,964 --> 00:45:54,030
- % And you could grow up%
- % Ooooh%

825
00:45:54,100 --> 00:45:59,632
- % Oooh%
- % To be anything%

826
00:45:59,701 --> 00:46:03,924
% But who would imagine%

827
00:46:03,989 --> 00:46:06,509
% A king%

828
00:46:06,580 --> 00:46:08,435
Everybody.

829
00:46:08,500 --> 00:46:11,534
% It was so clear%

830
00:46:11,605 --> 00:46:14,420
% When the Wise Men arrived%

831
00:46:14,485 --> 00:46:17,300
- Wait. Donkeys on this side.
- % And the angels%

832
00:46:17,365 --> 00:46:19,536
- Sorry.
- % Were singing%

833
00:46:19,605 --> 00:46:22,834
% Your name%

834
00:46:22,900 --> 00:46:27,057
% That the world
would be different%

835
00:46:27,125 --> 00:46:30,670
% 'Cause you were alive%

836
00:46:30,741 --> 00:46:34,221
% That's when heaven
stood still%

837
00:46:34,324 --> 00:46:37,456
% To proclaim%

838
00:46:37,525 --> 00:46:39,729
[Whispering]
Jessica.

839
00:46:39,797 --> 00:46:43,058
- % One day an angel%
- Take your baby. Smile.

840
00:46:43,125 --> 00:46:47,532
% Said quietly%

841
00:46:47,604 --> 00:46:50,638
% That soon he would bring%

842
00:46:50,709 --> 00:46:54,603
% Something special to me%

843
00:46:54,677 --> 00:46:59,150
- % Oooh%
- % And of all of the wonderful%

844
00:46:59,221 --> 00:47:04,043
- % Oooh%
- % Gifts he could bring%

845
00:47:04,117 --> 00:47:08,176
% Who would imagine%

846
00:47:08,245 --> 00:47:14,409
% A king% %

847
00:47:14,484 --> 00:47:17,867
- Sweet.
- Yeah.

848
00:47:20,244 --> 00:47:22,099
- [Jeremiah] Again.
- All right.

849
00:47:22,164 --> 00:47:24,848
You take this one solo, okay?

850
00:47:24,917 --> 00:47:27,372
- Okay?
- Comet's swingin'!

851
00:47:27,445 --> 00:47:29,299
- Ooh, look at that.
- Beautiful, isn't it?

852
00:47:29,365 --> 00:47:31,983
Uh-huh.
Sure is.

853
00:47:33,748 --> 00:47:35,691
Go in and try it on.

854
00:47:37,365 --> 00:47:40,180
We're supposed to be shopping
for Henry, remember?

855
00:47:40,245 --> 00:47:44,522
You with that nightgown on is
all the gift Henry would want.

856
00:47:44,597 --> 00:47:46,768
- Trust me.
- A gift from Jeremiah.

857
00:47:46,836 --> 00:47:50,098
- Oh. Ho, ho.
- Mmm.

858
00:47:51,605 --> 00:47:54,026
So how long do you think
he's gonna be with that snake?

859
00:47:54,100 --> 00:47:56,337
He'll be along soon.

860
00:47:56,405 --> 00:47:58,893
How'd you two meet, anyway?

861
00:47:58,965 --> 00:48:03,220
Hmm. We were in adjoining
strollers, and, uh...

862
00:48:03,317 --> 00:48:06,578
and one day I took his pacifier,
and he made a really big noise about it.

863
00:48:06,645 --> 00:48:08,652
Who wouldn't?

864
00:48:08,725 --> 00:48:11,180
You know, when he was about ten,
he started wearing suits to school.

865
00:48:11,284 --> 00:48:13,456
- What?
- Trying to impress me.

866
00:48:13,525 --> 00:48:15,859
[Laughing]
Obviously, it worked.

867
00:48:15,924 --> 00:48:18,575
He'd walk me home...

868
00:48:18,645 --> 00:48:21,296
and I always thought he was cuter
without his glasses, so...

869
00:48:21,365 --> 00:48:23,437
one day he took them off for me.

870
00:48:23,508 --> 00:48:26,574
[Laughing] And he slipped on the ice,
and fell right on his fanny.

871
00:48:26,644 --> 00:48:29,295
Sounds like love to me.

872
00:48:29,364 --> 00:48:32,910
Daddy said we were born friends.

873
00:48:35,124 --> 00:48:37,295
He did a lot for Henry,
your father.

874
00:48:37,364 --> 00:48:39,731
He was the best.

875
00:48:39,797 --> 00:48:42,350
Mommy.
Enough!

876
00:48:42,421 --> 00:48:44,592
% % ["Deck The Halls"]

877
00:48:44,661 --> 00:48:47,727
- Is it good, Dudley?
- Mm-hmm. Great.

878
00:48:47,797 --> 00:48:50,797
How is your food, Jeremiah?
Mmmmm.

879
00:48:50,869 --> 00:48:53,040
- Julia.
- Henry.

880
00:48:53,109 --> 00:48:56,240
Ah, Jeremiah.
Dudley!

881
00:48:56,308 --> 00:48:59,953
- Henry.
- Okay, Jer. Let's go shopping.

882
00:49:00,021 --> 00:49:02,355
- Wait, honey. What happened?
- I'll tell you later.

883
00:49:02,420 --> 00:49:04,243
- Come on. Come on.
- Henry, it is later.

884
00:49:04,309 --> 00:49:06,796
It's about an hour later
than when you were supposed to be here.

885
00:49:06,868 --> 00:49:08,876
- Now, what happened?
- It's a long story.

886
00:49:08,949 --> 00:49:10,891
You know, you and Julia need to talk.

887
00:49:10,964 --> 00:49:15,088
I can take Jeremiah shopping.
I'm an excellent gift consultant.

888
00:49:15,156 --> 00:49:17,066
Yes, Dudley.
I want Dudley.

889
00:49:17,141 --> 00:49:19,410
Wait a minute.
I wanted to take him shopping.

890
00:49:19,477 --> 00:49:21,779
You two have more important
things to talk about.

891
00:49:21,845 --> 00:49:23,852
- Dud-ley! Dud-ley! Dud-ley!
- Jeremiah.

892
00:49:23,925 --> 00:49:27,056
We'll be right across the street
at the toy store. Okay?

893
00:49:27,124 --> 00:49:29,034
- Julia! Julia!
- Dud-ley!

894
00:49:29,109 --> 00:49:32,589
- Jere-miah! Put your hat on.
- Dud-ley! Dud-ley!

895
00:49:32,661 --> 00:49:34,995
- So, who are we shopping for?
- Grandma.

896
00:49:35,060 --> 00:49:37,362
- Any idea what she wants?
- A new ashtray.

897
00:49:37,428 --> 00:49:40,657
- Mom took all her old ones.
- Let's get something for Hakim.

898
00:49:40,724 --> 00:49:42,415
So, what happened?

899
00:49:46,645 --> 00:49:49,579
Julia.

900
00:49:52,405 --> 00:49:54,892
L...

901
00:49:54,964 --> 00:49:58,576
I've decided to accept
Joe Hamilton's offer.

902
00:50:00,468 --> 00:50:03,086
Julia, did you hear me?

903
00:50:03,156 --> 00:50:07,085
- I heard you. I just can't
believe what I've heard.
- Then let me explain.

904
00:50:07,157 --> 00:50:09,164
Excuse me.
Can I get you anything?

905
00:50:09,237 --> 00:50:11,179
Oh, no, no, no.
No, thank you.

906
00:50:11,284 --> 00:50:13,935
Okay.

907
00:50:14,004 --> 00:50:17,779
Listen, Saul was there,
Mary Halford, Andy and Osbert.

908
00:50:17,844 --> 00:50:19,699
But what were they doing there?

909
00:50:19,764 --> 00:50:23,539
Every one of them was begging me,
arguing with me, blackmailing me.

910
00:50:23,604 --> 00:50:26,451
- Blackmail!
- They're gonna put in
a new boiler tomorrow.

911
00:50:26,517 --> 00:50:29,070
- Henry, he bought you for a boiler?
- Shh. Julia.

912
00:50:29,141 --> 00:50:31,148
[Diners Murmuring]

913
00:50:31,221 --> 00:50:34,570
Sorry. Sorry. Excuse us.
Of course not!

914
00:50:34,645 --> 00:50:37,165
- Oooooh...
- Julia, let me show you something.

915
00:50:37,237 --> 00:50:39,408
Julia, Julia...

916
00:50:39,476 --> 00:50:43,054
he is building the most beautiful church
you've ever seen.

917
00:50:43,124 --> 00:50:45,034
Look at that.
Day care center, youth center.

918
00:50:45,109 --> 00:50:47,530
Henry, he is building
a shrine to himself!

919
00:50:47,604 --> 00:50:51,314
Eight years, Julia.
And what do I have to show for it?

920
00:50:51,381 --> 00:50:55,854
So you give up our lives
without even talking to me, Henry?

921
00:50:55,925 --> 00:50:58,608
This solves all of our problems, Julia.
Why can't you see that?

922
00:50:58,676 --> 00:51:01,938
My father trusted you with St. Matt's.
How dare you walk out on it like this!

923
00:51:02,004 --> 00:51:04,426
All right, all right.
Your father was a saint, and I'm not!

924
00:51:04,500 --> 00:51:07,217
But I'm here, Julia, and he isn't.

925
00:51:10,485 --> 00:51:13,005
I'm sorry, Julia.

926
00:51:13,076 --> 00:51:15,378
Give me the car keys, Henry!

927
00:51:15,444 --> 00:51:17,964
Julia!

928
00:51:18,036 --> 00:51:20,425
- Julia, please sit down.
- Give me the keys, Henry.

929
00:51:20,500 --> 00:51:24,275
Would you kindly give her the keys?
I have customers sitting here.

930
00:51:24,340 --> 00:51:26,195
Sorry. Sorry.

931
00:51:26,260 --> 00:51:28,365
Julia, please listen to me.

932
00:51:28,436 --> 00:51:31,949
Henry, I can't.
I don't even know who you are anymore.

933
00:51:32,020 --> 00:51:34,159
Julia.

934
00:51:36,341 --> 00:51:38,762
Come on, Jeremiah.
We're leaving.

935
00:51:38,837 --> 00:51:40,746
I got Daddy's present.

936
00:51:40,820 --> 00:51:43,854
And I bought a fire engine for Hakim.

937
00:51:43,925 --> 00:51:45,779
It was on sale.

938
00:51:45,845 --> 00:51:48,692
Yes, that's wonderful, honey.
That's wonderful.

939
00:51:48,756 --> 00:51:51,309
[Car Doors Closing]

940
00:51:53,589 --> 00:51:57,451
All right. You're going to have
to support him now, Julia.

941
00:51:57,525 --> 00:52:00,340
You hear me?
Now is when he needs you most.

942
00:52:00,405 --> 00:52:02,893
Mama, I can't support what's wrong.

943
00:52:02,964 --> 00:52:06,063
Preachin' God's word is never wrong,
no matter where you do it from.

944
00:52:08,308 --> 00:52:11,178
He didn't even discuss it with me.

945
00:52:11,284 --> 00:52:13,935
Daddy would have never
made a decision like that
without discussing it with you.

946
00:52:14,004 --> 00:52:18,412
Sure he would. Your Daddy kept
things from me all the time.
Especially church business.

947
00:52:18,485 --> 00:52:20,754
Well, it was different
in those days.

948
00:52:20,821 --> 00:52:24,879
Those days!
Child, men ain't changed since Adam!

949
00:52:24,949 --> 00:52:29,356
And he gave up one of his own ribs,
just so he could have somebody
to keep things from!

950
00:52:33,940 --> 00:52:37,617
You know, gettin'angry
at a dead tree is not gonna help.

951
00:52:37,685 --> 00:52:40,980
Yeah, but it wouldn't look good
to punch out a pastor, either.

952
00:52:41,044 --> 00:52:44,688
No, you don't... you don't...
you don't mean that...

953
00:52:44,757 --> 00:52:46,644
'Cause you know you love him.

954
00:52:46,708 --> 00:52:48,650
Yeah, he knows it, too.
That's the problem.

955
00:52:48,724 --> 00:52:51,953
He knows I'll always be there,
just like a pet.

956
00:52:52,020 --> 00:52:54,671
- Ouch!
- See? God doesn't like ugly.

957
00:52:54,740 --> 00:52:56,715
- Let me see.
- [Whimpering]

958
00:52:59,444 --> 00:53:01,354
You ever had your palm read?

959
00:53:01,652 --> 00:53:04,499
[Chuckles]

960
00:53:04,565 --> 00:53:07,020
Okay.

961
00:53:12,149 --> 00:53:15,923
I see a beautiful woman
with a good heart.

962
00:53:15,989 --> 00:53:20,723
Only has to open her eyes to realize
that everything she ever wanted...

963
00:53:20,789 --> 00:53:23,276
she already has.

964
00:53:23,348 --> 00:53:26,414
You didn't even look at my hand.

965
00:53:26,484 --> 00:53:29,103
But I held it.

966
00:53:29,173 --> 00:53:32,817
Do you see Henry and me?

967
00:53:32,884 --> 00:53:37,259
Hmmm... let's see.

968
00:53:37,332 --> 00:53:39,699
- Ow! Ow! Ow!
- Ohhh.

969
00:53:39,764 --> 00:53:41,935
Oh, it's so hot,
I had to let it go.

970
00:53:42,004 --> 00:53:44,339
You must be talking about my past.

971
00:53:44,404 --> 00:53:46,640
- Mrs. Biggs, you forgot this.
- Thanks.

972
00:53:46,709 --> 00:53:49,043
Every fire dies sometime,
Dudley.

973
00:53:49,108 --> 00:53:52,337
What do you do when you have to decide
if the memory of it is enough?

974
00:53:52,372 --> 00:53:54,706
- What do you do?
- Yeah.

975
00:53:54,772 --> 00:53:58,155
What you do is you... you go dancing,
that's what you do. You go out.

976
00:53:58,229 --> 00:53:59,952
- Dancing?
- Yes.

977
00:54:00,020 --> 00:54:04,144
You're gonna go dancing,
put on a beautiful dress,
make your husband break out the cologne.

978
00:54:04,212 --> 00:54:06,067
- Have you met my husband?
- That's right, I met him.

979
00:54:06,132 --> 00:54:09,067
- He hasn't taken me out in...
- Far too long. That's my point.

980
00:54:09,141 --> 00:54:13,069
But tonight's gonna be different.
Tonight you're gonna strike a match.

981
00:54:13,140 --> 00:54:17,264
No, not a match, a, a firecracker!
You'll see.

982
00:54:17,332 --> 00:54:19,274
[Chuckles]

983
00:54:19,349 --> 00:54:24,051
You take your coat off, you go upstairs
and you take your wife out dancing.

984
00:54:24,116 --> 00:54:25,971
Can't do it.
Not tonight.

985
00:54:26,036 --> 00:54:28,905
Henry, you and Julia need this.

986
00:54:28,980 --> 00:54:32,722
Mr. Kingman needs his minister
with him at the hospital,
and the seniors need blankets.

987
00:54:32,789 --> 00:54:35,025
You're only one man, Henry.

988
00:54:35,092 --> 00:54:37,842
Things don't get fixed
waiting for the next guy to do it.

989
00:54:37,908 --> 00:54:39,980
- Including marriages.
- Dudley!

990
00:54:40,052 --> 00:54:42,321
Henry!

991
00:54:42,389 --> 00:54:44,941
You already told her,
didn't you?

992
00:54:45,012 --> 00:54:47,468
She's upstairs dressing right now...

993
00:54:47,540 --> 00:54:49,907
- and once again
I'm gonna look like the bad guy.
- Not if you go.

994
00:54:49,972 --> 00:54:52,306
- Dudley!
- What? I'm just trying to help you.

995
00:54:52,372 --> 00:54:54,543
You're just trying to help.

996
00:54:54,612 --> 00:54:57,198
All right, you can help...
by taking her.

997
00:54:57,268 --> 00:54:59,090
- Me?
- Yes, you.

998
00:54:59,188 --> 00:55:01,425
- You're missing the point, Henry.
- No, no.

999
00:55:01,492 --> 00:55:06,031
The point is...
Mr. Kingman won't wait.

1000
00:55:06,100 --> 00:55:08,849
Now, you go, tell me all about it later.

1001
00:55:08,917 --> 00:55:12,364
- [Sighs]
- And you make sure
you tell her I'm sorry.

1002
00:55:12,436 --> 00:55:15,022
- [Dudley] Ohh, Henry.
- Good night.

1003
00:55:15,092 --> 00:55:16,947
- Henry.
- Not too late.

1004
00:55:17,012 --> 00:55:18,867
- Henry.
- And no drinking.

1005
00:55:18,932 --> 00:55:22,641
It was not supposed
to go like this.

1006
00:55:22,708 --> 00:55:24,781
[Jeremiah]
Good night, Mommy.

1007
00:55:24,852 --> 00:55:26,707
[Julia]
Okay, good night.

1008
00:55:26,772 --> 00:55:29,325
[Marguerite] Don't worry about us.
I'm gonna give 'em a hot bath...

1009
00:55:29,396 --> 00:55:32,145
and then we're gonna play Monopoly...
for real money!

1010
00:55:32,212 --> 00:55:33,586
[Jeremiah]
Yea!

1011
00:55:35,700 --> 00:55:37,554
[Whispering]
How do I look?

1012
00:55:37,620 --> 00:55:40,587
Oh! Oh, my!

1013
00:55:40,660 --> 00:55:42,569
Henry?

1014
00:55:44,180 --> 00:55:47,214
Henry? Henry?

1015
00:55:50,452 --> 00:55:53,266
- Where's Henry?
- He said... He said he's sorry.

1016
00:55:53,332 --> 00:55:57,707
- He's sorry?
- Yeah, he had to go.

1017
00:55:57,780 --> 00:56:00,463
One of the congregation
is in the hospital. Mr. Kingman.

1018
00:56:00,532 --> 00:56:04,144
Oh, yeah.
He's been sick a long time.

1019
00:56:04,212 --> 00:56:06,895
I'll call his wife tomorrow.

1020
00:56:09,492 --> 00:56:13,518
Look, Julia,
he suggested that I, uh...

1021
00:56:13,588 --> 00:56:17,385
pinch-hit for him,
if that's okay with you.

1022
00:56:19,252 --> 00:56:21,488
Hmm?

1023
00:56:21,652 --> 00:56:24,783
[Doorman]
Welcome to Jazzie's, folks. Come on in.

1024
00:56:24,852 --> 00:56:26,707
- Thanks.
- Thank you.

1025
00:56:26,772 --> 00:56:28,431
- [People Clapping]
- My brother.

1026
00:56:40,820 --> 00:56:44,944
[Chattering, Laughter]

1027
00:56:45,012 --> 00:56:46,922
Ahhh!

1028
00:56:48,532 --> 00:56:52,361
Nice, huh? Dancing. Do you dance?
I bet you're a good dancer.

1029
00:56:52,436 --> 00:56:55,338
It's been a long time.

1030
00:56:55,412 --> 00:56:57,714
You want to dance?

1031
00:56:57,780 --> 00:56:59,820
Why not?
[Laughs]

1032
00:56:59,892 --> 00:57:02,380
- All right.
- Give it a shot.

1033
00:57:02,452 --> 00:57:06,194
- Bust a move. Right.
- Bust a move. [Laughs]

1034
00:57:13,460 --> 00:57:17,235
It doesn't seem like we're dancing
right for this music, huh?

1035
00:57:18,452 --> 00:57:21,322
[Man Laughing]
Get down.

1036
00:57:21,396 --> 00:57:25,869
- Oh, yeah. Yeah, I see what you mean.
- [Snapping Fingers]

1037
00:57:25,940 --> 00:57:28,209
Yeah.
[Laughs]

1038
00:57:30,516 --> 00:57:33,615
[Grunting]

1039
00:57:35,091 --> 00:57:36,946
Oh, my.

1040
00:57:37,011 --> 00:57:40,273
[Man] Go, brother!
Ooh, hit it!

1041
00:57:40,340 --> 00:57:43,155
- [Laughter, Chattering]
- What's he doing?

1042
00:57:46,292 --> 00:57:48,681
Mmm!

1043
00:57:52,020 --> 00:57:54,670
Ooh.

1044
00:57:56,500 --> 00:57:59,020
- What's that one?
- The Popeye.

1045
00:57:59,091 --> 00:58:01,230
- The Popeye. Okay.
- [Laughing]

1046
00:58:01,300 --> 00:58:04,366
- It's comin' back now.
- I guess.

1047
00:58:04,436 --> 00:58:06,291
[Screams]

1048
00:58:06,356 --> 00:58:09,258
Whoo! You get out
about as much as I do.

1049
00:58:09,332 --> 00:58:13,642
Less! Even less!
[Laughing]

1050
00:58:13,716 --> 00:58:15,920
[Dudley]
Oh, there we go!

1051
00:58:15,988 --> 00:58:18,835
- [Julia] Oh, you're swimming.
- Yeah, backstroking.

1052
00:58:18,899 --> 00:58:22,216
[Laughter Continues]

1053
00:58:22,292 --> 00:58:25,358
- Jules!
- Bristloe!

1054
00:58:25,428 --> 00:58:28,297
- How you doin', sweet thing?
- Oh, my Lord!

1055
00:58:28,372 --> 00:58:31,339
- I thought you were in Paris.
- I was, but I've been back a while.

1056
00:58:31,412 --> 00:58:33,746
You and Henry don't
come by here much anymore.

1057
00:58:33,812 --> 00:58:36,779
Henry's been real busy.
But it's great to see you!

1058
00:58:36,852 --> 00:58:40,746
- You too! How you doin', sweet thing?
- Oh, I'm okay.

1059
00:58:40,820 --> 00:58:43,024
Dudley, Bristloe.
Bristloe, Dudley.

1060
00:58:43,092 --> 00:58:46,441
- Oh, hey. How ya doin'?
- A pleasure, a pleasure.

1061
00:58:46,516 --> 00:58:50,378
If Henry hadn't helped me
with that plane ticket,
I never would've gotten to Paris.

1062
00:58:50,452 --> 00:58:52,623
I tell you,
I owe that man everything.

1063
00:58:52,692 --> 00:58:54,699
- You should call him and tell him.
- I will.

1064
00:58:54,771 --> 00:58:56,943
Do that.
He'd love to hear from you.

1065
00:58:57,012 --> 00:59:00,459
Why don't we all
just sit down and visit?

1066
00:59:00,531 --> 00:59:03,019
Yeah.

1067
00:59:06,612 --> 00:59:09,907
- Okay.
- [Bandleader] Thank you. Thank you.

1068
00:59:09,972 --> 00:59:12,939
So, Bristloe,
are you and Maxine still together?

1069
00:59:13,011 --> 00:59:14,953
- Oh, you better believe it.
- Oh, good.

1070
00:59:15,028 --> 00:59:18,225
She still calls six times a day
to make sure I'm being a good boy.

1071
00:59:18,292 --> 00:59:21,805
Fine woman, that Maxine.
You married, Dudley?

1072
00:59:21,876 --> 00:59:23,785
No, no.

1073
00:59:23,860 --> 00:59:27,635
No, I've never been lucky enough
to meet someone like Maxine... or Julia.

1074
00:59:27,700 --> 00:59:29,675
Ain't that the truth?

1075
00:59:29,748 --> 00:59:32,465
Used to be a time this little girl
could come by here every night.

1076
00:59:32,532 --> 00:59:34,768
- Yeah? You used to come in here?
- Sure.

1077
00:59:34,836 --> 00:59:38,219
Henry proposed to me
right over there, in that booth.

1078
00:59:38,292 --> 00:59:40,942
- Get outta here! Right over there?
- That's right.

1079
00:59:41,012 --> 00:59:43,281
- Those were the good old days, huh?
- Sure were.

1080
00:59:43,348 --> 00:59:45,715
- Couldn't squeeze a dime between 'em.
- Whew.

1081
00:59:45,780 --> 00:59:48,049
She used to go on stage
and torch the place down.

1082
00:59:48,116 --> 00:59:50,799
Get outta here.

1083
00:59:50,868 --> 00:59:54,926
Now she just sings for the Lord.
Not that that's bad. [Laughs]

1084
00:59:54,996 --> 00:59:57,168
No, no, no.
That's good.

1085
00:59:57,236 --> 01:00:00,683
Let me tell you somethin'.
Ever want to know what lovin'
really sounds like...

1086
01:00:00,756 --> 01:00:03,506
- she's got that secret in her voice.
- Oh, Bristloe, please.

1087
01:00:03,572 --> 01:00:06,354
Why don't you share
that secret with us, Julia?

1088
01:00:06,419 --> 01:00:10,162
- Come on, remind us.
- No. It's been years, a long time.

1089
01:00:10,228 --> 01:00:13,261
- You still do it in B?
- No, no, Bristloe. I don't do it at all.

1090
01:00:13,332 --> 01:00:15,820
Well, I'd like to know
what love really sounds like.

1091
01:00:15,892 --> 01:00:18,347
- Well, that solves that problem.
- Bristloe.

1092
01:00:18,420 --> 01:00:21,682
- I don't know the song.
- Don't want to hear another word.

1093
01:00:21,748 --> 01:00:26,090
- I don't...
- We want to hear you sing.
You sang it for Henry.

1094
01:00:26,196 --> 01:00:28,585
[Julia]
I should be going home.

1095
01:00:28,820 --> 01:00:32,365
- We're going to play this in B.
Just follow me, okay?
- Okay.

1096
01:00:32,436 --> 01:00:35,884
- Follow him, guys.
- You go out there. Go on. Yeah.

1097
01:00:35,956 --> 01:00:39,022
- [Dudley Applauding]
- Go on, sing it for Henry.

1098
01:00:39,092 --> 01:00:41,547
% % [Piano]

1099
01:00:41,620 --> 01:00:44,467
[Applauding Continues]

1100
01:00:44,532 --> 01:00:48,426
No. No.

1101
01:00:51,412 --> 01:00:53,746
Here we go.

1102
01:00:57,236 --> 01:01:01,579
% I believe in you and me%

1103
01:01:01,651 --> 01:01:05,426
% I believe that we will be%

1104
01:01:05,491 --> 01:01:10,031
% In love eternally%

1105
01:01:10,100 --> 01:01:14,355
% Well, as far as I can see%

1106
01:01:14,420 --> 01:01:16,908
% You will always be%

1107
01:01:16,980 --> 01:01:20,209
% The one%

1108
01:01:21,555 --> 01:01:24,904
% For me%

1109
01:01:24,980 --> 01:01:28,592
% Oh, yes, you will%

1110
01:01:28,660 --> 01:01:32,272
% I believe in dreams again%

1111
01:01:32,340 --> 01:01:37,075
% I believe that love
will never end%

1112
01:01:37,140 --> 01:01:40,784
% And like the river finds%

1113
01:01:40,851 --> 01:01:43,753
% The sea%

1114
01:01:43,828 --> 01:01:47,658
% I was lost%

1115
01:01:47,731 --> 01:01:52,466
% Now I'm free%

1116
01:01:52,531 --> 01:01:56,143
% 'Cause I believe in you%

1117
01:01:56,211 --> 01:01:59,757
% And me, oh, oh my%

1118
01:01:59,828 --> 01:02:03,952
% Well, maybe I'm a fool%

1119
01:02:04,020 --> 01:02:07,664
% To feel the way I do%

1120
01:02:07,731 --> 01:02:11,986
% But I would play
the fool forever%

1121
01:02:12,052 --> 01:02:18,064
% Just to be
with you forever%

1122
01:02:18,132 --> 01:02:21,907
% I believe in miracles%

1123
01:02:21,972 --> 01:02:26,761
% And love's a miracle%

1124
01:02:26,835 --> 01:02:30,480
% And yes, baby
you're a dream%

1125
01:02:30,548 --> 01:02:34,028
% Come true, ohhh%

1126
01:02:34,100 --> 01:02:37,416
% I was lost%

1127
01:02:37,491 --> 01:02:41,648
% Now I'm free%

1128
01:02:41,716 --> 01:02:44,433
% Oh, darling, I believe%

1129
01:02:44,500 --> 01:02:49,104
% In you and me%

1130
01:02:49,171 --> 01:02:53,361
% See, I was lost%

1131
01:02:53,428 --> 01:02:58,545
% Now I'm free%

1132
01:02:58,611 --> 01:03:02,768
% 'Cause I believe in you%

1133
01:03:02,836 --> 01:03:09,230
% And me%

1134
01:03:09,300 --> 01:03:13,904
% Oooh, yeah
Oh, yes, I do%

1135
01:03:13,971 --> 01:03:17,648
% I believe in you and%

1136
01:03:17,715 --> 01:03:23,825
% Me% %

1137
01:03:31,956 --> 01:03:35,982
[Julia] Thank you.
Thank you very much.

1138
01:03:36,051 --> 01:03:39,826
[Laughing]
You're bad.

1139
01:03:39,891 --> 01:03:42,608
One for you.

1140
01:03:42,675 --> 01:03:45,010
One for me.

1141
01:03:45,076 --> 01:03:47,050
And one for the tree.

1142
01:03:47,156 --> 01:03:50,931
- Thank you.
- I got your Christmas present yesterday.

1143
01:03:50,996 --> 01:03:53,003
You did?
What'd you get?

1144
01:03:53,076 --> 01:03:55,945
I can't tell you.
It's a secret.

1145
01:03:56,019 --> 01:03:58,288
What are you getting Mom for Christmas?

1146
01:03:58,356 --> 01:04:00,777
I don't know.
What do you think I should get her?

1147
01:04:00,852 --> 01:04:03,787
I think she'd like to go to bed.

1148
01:04:05,236 --> 01:04:07,570
Excuse me, young man?

1149
01:04:07,635 --> 01:04:11,247
She was looking at a nightie
in the store window with Dudley.

1150
01:04:11,316 --> 01:04:13,171
Was she now?

1151
01:04:13,236 --> 01:04:15,341
All right, come on, young man.
Sleep time.

1152
01:04:15,411 --> 01:04:18,378
Wait for your mama to get home,
you'll be too big for the bed.

1153
01:04:18,451 --> 01:04:22,379
Go get some more Vicks on your chest.
See if we can rid of that stuffy nose.

1154
01:04:22,451 --> 01:04:25,102
I think you were born
with a stuffy nose. Come on, here.

1155
01:04:25,171 --> 01:04:28,139
- [Jeremiah] Good night, Daddy.
- Good night, son.

1156
01:04:32,532 --> 01:04:35,347
[Laughing]
Oh, thank you.

1157
01:04:35,412 --> 01:04:38,161
- [Driver] Have a good evening.
- Thank you.

1158
01:04:38,228 --> 01:04:41,708
- Did you have a good time?
- Are you kidding?
I had a great time. You?

1159
01:04:41,780 --> 01:04:44,529
I had a ball.
You're not such a bad dancer.

1160
01:04:44,596 --> 01:04:47,410
- I haven't had so much fun
in a long time.
- I did too.

1161
01:04:47,476 --> 01:04:50,225
- I heard you singing.
- Yeah, I was about to get
up there with you.

1162
01:04:50,291 --> 01:04:53,008
- I'm so glad you didn't.
- % I believe in miracles%

1163
01:04:53,075 --> 01:04:56,392
- Shh! They're probably all asleep.
- Not all of us.

1164
01:04:56,468 --> 01:04:59,021
- Henry.
- Dudley.

1165
01:04:59,092 --> 01:05:02,703
I guess I don't have to ask
if you had a... good time.

1166
01:05:02,803 --> 01:05:05,105
We did. We went to Jazzies.

1167
01:05:05,172 --> 01:05:08,467
Some of the old band
was there, and...

1168
01:05:08,531 --> 01:05:11,314
You've been at Jazzie's?

1169
01:05:11,380 --> 01:05:14,576
Yeah. Yeah.
Bristloe was there too.

1170
01:05:14,643 --> 01:05:17,513
- Henry, your wife got on stage.
- Oh, wait, wait.

1171
01:05:17,588 --> 01:05:19,530
You went singing
at Jazzie's all night?

1172
01:05:19,603 --> 01:05:23,280
- You told me to take her out.
